                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone is inscribed with a Roman-letter inscription in two lines, reading vertically downwards. A partially corresponding Ogham inscription begins on the upper left edge of the stone, reading upwards, and continues on the right edge of the stone, reading downwards. The inscriptions are likely <rs type="execution" key="carved" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/168.html"> carved</rs> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 439-440).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>In the Ogham inscription <q>the gaps are large enough to have carried more than one letter, and need not have consisted of vowel-notches only...the Ps appear to be represented by crosses of three lines, a varition on one of the forfeda signs</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440). The Roman-letter inscription is <q>mostly Roman capitals, but with uncial form of E, and Ps with the vertical stroke descending below the line; Rs with open loop and tail approaching the horizontal; enlarged S; VM ligatured...suggesting that capitals were used with rapidity in written form, and not restricted to monumental use. Perhaps worked from a tablet exemplar; on the stone the letterer has started enlarging the letters in too small a scale with what looks like a lower-case P, but has scaled up - in a rising crescendo - to full capital for the second P in PUMPEIUS. Similarly the scale of the S has given some difficulty, the inscription ending with an S twice the size of the preceeding letter V</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440).
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
