            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                <p><title>Ogham</title>: No complete translation is suggested for the Ogham inscription <q><foreign xml:lang="pgl">Pumpeius</foreign> seems likely to have been rendered in the ogam but there seems to be no correlation to the remainder of the two inscriptions</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" n="2">
                    <p><title>Latin</title>: '<foreign xml:lang="pgl">Pumpeius</foreign><foreign xml:lang="pgl">Carantorius</foreign>(lies here)'</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                        <p>The Ogham inscription appears to correspond to the Roman-letter inscription in its first half <q>the ogam P[O]P[, if correctly restored...may preserve the original vowel <hi rend="italic">Pompeius</hi>...[most likely] the omission of the /m/ is due to Vulgar Latin as in SEPRONIVS (<hi rend="italic">RIB 1:</hi> no. 686), and Continental forms such as <hi rend="italic">Popeianus</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Pepeia</hi>...If POPIAS is the correct reading, the -AS may be the Irish nominative ending corresponding to Latin <hi rend="italic">-us</hi> and IA rather than EA could be a hypercorrect spelling...The <hi rend="italic">forfid</hi> for P is one of the additional ogam letters invented for this un-Irish sound</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440-1). The rest of the inscription does not appear to correspond to the Roman-letter inscription. <q>ROLACUN...offers the Irish etymology <hi rend="italic">*Ro-ola-kun-</hi>, 'very large hound'... ILLUNA could be related to the OI name <hi rend="italic">Illan(n), Elann</hi> and word <hi rend="italic">ela</hi> 'swan', as in <hi rend="italic">CIIC:</hi> no. 79, ELUNA in Ireland</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 441).</p>
                        <p>In the Roman-letter inscription, <q>PVMPEIVS for <hi rend="italic">Pompeius</hi> may show the Welsh development of /um/ [from] /om/...CARANTORIVS is definitely not Irish; it is the forerunner of OW <hi rend="italic">Cerenhir</hi>, W. <hi rend="italic">Cerennhyr</hi>...such names in <hi rend="italic">-orius</hi> have been much discussed</q> but no definitive interpretation of its significance is offered (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440-1).</p>
            </div>
